Raw dev notes -- Kicking off the LLM Code Token Toolkit

Okay, so I finally bit the bullet and started that little side project I've been mulling over for weeks. The `claude-code-token-toolkit` (a bit of a mouthful, I know) is basically my personal attempt to get a handle on LLM token limits when working with code. I'm constantly bumping up against context window limits, and I want a tool that can help me understand the token cost of my codebases, break them down, and maybe even optimize them for feeding into various LLMs. It's a personal pain point, and I figured, why not build my own solution?

This past day was all about getting the initial scaffolding up. The very first commit was "Initial commit: catalog + analyzer," which felt like a huge win just to get *something* down. Right now, the "catalog" is just a placeholder for how I'll eventually store and organize code snippets, and the "analyzer" is where the token counting magic will happen. It's super basic, but it's a start.

After that, it was a flurry of naming and documentation. Renamed the repo to `claude-code-token-toolkit` (after some internal debate, because naming things is always the hardest part, right?). Then I spent a surprising amount of time sharpening the README. I added a "vision" section, which felt important for clarifying my own thoughts, and an "honest current-state" to manage expectations (mostly my own). Also got a basic TODO list going, which is always satisfying. All these commits happened on the same day, a real burst of initial energy.

What was hard? Honestly, just getting that "Initial commit" out. I had the idea floating around for ages, but translating it into actual code, even just a couple of empty files, felt like pulling teeth. There's always that blank page syndrome. Also, defining the initial scope was tricky. How much should the "catalog" do? How deep should the "analyzer" go right out of the gate? I decided to keep it super lean for now, focusing purely on the token counting aspect first. And yeah, the naming. I went through about five different names before landing on this one, which is descriptive but maybe a little clunky.

Personally, it felt great to finally *start*. I've been talking about this idea for a while, and seeing it take shape, even in this nascent form, is really motivating. It's a good reminder that the biggest hurdle is often just getting off the starting line. I also learned (again) the value of documenting my intentions early, even for a personal project. Writing out the "vision" and "current state" in the README helped solidify what I'm trying to achieve and gave me a clearer roadmap. It's satisfying to build a tool that directly addresses a problem I'm facing.

Next up: Implement the actual tokenization logic.
